line1_text: Awake, my St. John! leave all meaner things
line2_text: To low ambition, and the pride of kings.

line1_text: Let us (since life can little more supply
line2_text: Than just to look about us and to die)

line1_text: Expatiate free o'er all this scene of man;
line2_text: A mighty maze! but not without a plan;

line1_text: A wild, where weeds and flowers promiscuous shoot;
line2_text: Or garden tempting with forbidden fruit.

line1_text: Together let us beat this ample field,
line2_text: Try what the open, what the covert yield;

line1_text: The latent tracts, the giddy heights, explore
line2_text: Of all who blindly creep, or sightless soar;

line1_text: Eye Nature's walks, shoot Folly as it flies,
line2_text: And catch the manners living as they rise;

line1_text: Laugh where we must, be candid where we can;
line2_text: But vindicate the ways of God to man.

line1_text: I.  Say first, of God above, or man below
line2_text: What can we reason, but from what we know?

line1_text: Of man, what see we but his station here,
line2_text: From which to reason, or to which refer?

line1_text: Through worlds unnumbered though the God be known,
line2_text: 'Tis ours to trace Him only in our own.

line1_text: He, who through vast immensity can pierce,
line2_text: See worlds on worlds compose one universe,

line1_text: Observe how system into system runs,
line2_text: What other planets circle other suns,

line1_text: What varied being peoples every star,
line2_text: May tell why Heaven has made us as we are.

line1_text: But of this frame, the bearings, and the ties,
line2_text: The strong connections, nice dependencies,

line1_text: Gradations just, has thy pervading soul
line2_text: Looked through? or can a part contain the whole?

line1_text: Is the great chain, that draws all to agree,
line2_text: And drawn supports, upheld by God, or thee?

line1_text: II.  Presumptuous man! the reason wouldst thou find,
line2_text: Why formed so weak, so little, and so blind?

line1_text: First, if thou canst, the harder reason guess,
line2_text: Why formed no weaker, blinder, and no less;

line1_text: Ask of thy mother earth, why oaks are made
line2_text: Taller or stronger than the weeds they shade?

line1_text: Or ask of yonder argent fields above,
line2_text: Why Jove's satellites are less than Jove?

line1_text: Of systems possible, if 'tis confest
line2_text: That wisdom infinite must form the best,

line1_text: Where all must full or not coherent be,
line2_text: And all that rises, rise in due degree;

line1_text: Then in the scale of reasoning life, 'tis plain,
line2_text: There must be, somewhere, such a rank as man:

line1_text: And all the question (wrangle e'er so long)
line2_text: Is only this, if God has placed him wrong?

line1_text: Respecting man, whatever wrong we call,
line2_text: May, must be right, as relative to all.

line1_text: In human works, though laboured on with pain,
line2_text: A thousand movements scarce one purpose gain;

line1_text: In God's one single can its end produce;
line2_text: Yet serves to second too some other use.

line1_text: So man, who here seems principal alone,
line2_text: Perhaps acts second to some sphere unknown,

line1_text: Touches some wheel, or verges to some goal;
line2_text: 'Tis but a part we see, and not a whole.

line1_text: When the proud steed shall know why man restrains
line2_text: His fiery course, or drives him o'er the plains:

line1_text: When the dull ox, why now he breaks the clod,
line2_text: Is now a victim, and now Egypt's god:

line1_text: Then shall man's pride and dulness comprehend
line2_text: His actions', passions', being's, use and end;

line1_text: Why doing, suffering, checked, impelled; and why
line2_text: This hour a slave, the next a deity.

line1_text: Then say not man's imperfect, Heaven in fault;
line2_text: Say rather man's as perfect as he ought:

line1_text: His knowledge measured to his state and place;
line2_text: His time a moment, and a point his space.

line1_text: If to be perfect in a certain sphere,
line2_text: What matter, soon or late, or here or there?

line1_text: The blest to-day is as completely so,
line2_text: As who began a thousand years ago.

line1_text: III.  Heaven from all creatures hides the book of Fate,
line2_text: All but the page prescribed, their present state:

line1_text: From brutes what men, from men what spirits know:
line2_text: Or who could suffer being here below?

line1_text: The lamb thy riot dooms to bleed to-day,
line2_text: Had he thy reason, would he skip and play?

line1_text: Pleased to the last, he crops the flowery food,
line2_text: And licks the hand just raised to shed his blood.

line1_text: Oh, blindness to the future! kindly given,
line2_text: That each may fill the circle, marked by Heaven:

line1_text: Who sees with equal eye, as God of all,
line2_text: A hero perish, or a sparrow fall,

line1_text: Atoms or systems into ruin hurled,
line2_text: And now a bubble burst, and now a world.

line1_text: Hope humbly, then; with trembling pinions soar;
line2_text: Wait the great teacher Death; and God adore.

line1_text: What future bliss, He gives not thee to know,
line2_text: But gives that hope to be thy blessing now.

line1_text: Hope springs eternal in the human breast:
line2_text: Man never is, but always to be blest:

line1_text: The soul, uneasy and confined from home,
line2_text: Rests and expatiates in a life to come.

line1_text: Lo, the poor Indian! whose untutored mind
line2_text: Sees God in clouds, or hears Him in the wind;

line1_text: His soul, proud science never taught to stray
line2_text: Far as the solar walk, or milky way;

line1_text: Yet simple Nature to his hope has given,
line2_text: Behind the cloud-topped hill, an humbler heaven;

line1_text: Some safer world in depth of woods embraced,
line2_text: Some happier island in the watery waste,

line1_text: Where slaves once more their native land behold,
line2_text: No fiends torment, no Christians thirst for gold.

line1_text: To be, contents his natural desire,
line2_text: He asks no angel's wing, no seraph's fire;

line1_text: But thinks, admitted to that equal sky,
line2_text: His faithful dog shall bear him company.

line1_text: IV.  Go, wiser thou! and, in thy scale of sense,
line2_text: Weigh thy opinion against providence;

line1_text: Call imperfection what thou fanciest such,
line2_text: Say, here He gives too little, there too much;

line1_text: Destroy all creatures for thy sport or gust,
line2_text: Yet cry, if man's unhappy, God's unjust;

line1_text: If man alone engross not Heaven's high care,
line2_text: Alone made perfect here, immortal there:

line1_text: Snatch from His hand the balance and the rod,
line2_text: Re-judge His justice, be the God of God.

line1_text: In pride, in reasoning pride, our error lies;
line2_text: All quit their sphere, and rush into the skies.

line1_text: Pride still is aiming at the blest abodes,
line2_text: Men would be angels, angels would be gods.

line1_text: Aspiring to be gods, if angels fell,
line2_text: Aspiring to be angels, men rebel:

line1_text: And who but wishes to invert the laws
line2_text: Of order, sins against the Eternal Cause.

line1_text: V.  Ask for what end the heavenly bodies shine,
line2_text: Earth for whose use?  Pride answers, "'Tis for mine:

line1_text: For me kind Nature wakes her genial power,
line2_text: Suckles each herb, and spreads out every flower;

line1_text: Annual for me, the grape, the rose renew
line2_text: The juice nectareous, and the balmy dew;

line1_text: For me, the mine a thousand treasures brings;
line2_text: For me, health gushes from a thousand springs;

line1_text: Seas roll to waft me, suns to light me rise;
line2_text: My footstool earth, my canopy the skies."

line1_text: But errs not Nature from this gracious end,
line2_text: From burning suns when livid deaths descend,

line1_text: When earthquakes swallow, or when tempests sweep
line2_text: Towns to one grave, whole nations to the deep?

line1_text: "No, ('tis replied) the first Almighty Cause
line2_text: Acts not by partial, but by general laws;

line1_text: The exceptions few; some change since all began;
line2_text: And what created perfect?"--Why then man?

line1_text: If the great end be human happiness,
line2_text: Then Nature deviates; and can man do less?

line1_text: As much that end a constant course requires
line2_text: Of showers and sunshine, as of man's desires;

line1_text: As much eternal springs and cloudless skies,
line2_text: As men for ever temperate, calm, and wise.

line1_text: If plagues or earthquakes break not Heaven's design,
line2_text: Why then a Borgia, or a Catiline?

line1_text: Who knows but He, whose hand the lightning forms,
line2_text: Who heaves old ocean, and who wings the storms;

line1_text: Pours fierce ambition in a Caesar's mind,
line2_text: Or turns young Ammon loose to scourge mankind?

line1_text: From pride, from pride, our very reasoning springs;
line2_text: Account for moral, as for natural things:

line1_text: Why charge we heaven in those, in these acquit?
line2_text: In both, to reason right is to submit.

line1_text: Better for us, perhaps, it might appear,
line2_text: Were there all harmony, all virtue here;

line1_text: That never air or ocean felt the wind;
line2_text: That never passion discomposed the mind.

line1_text: But all subsists by elemental strife;
line2_text: And passions are the elements of life.

line1_text: The general order, since the whole began,
line2_text: Is kept in nature, and is kept in man.

line1_text: VI.  What would this man?  Now upward will he soar,
line2_text: And little less than angel, would be more;

line1_text: Now looking downwards, just as grieved appears
line2_text: To want the strength of bulls, the fur of bears

line1_text: Made for his use all creatures if he call,
line2_text: Say what their use, had he the powers of all?

line1_text: Nature to these, without profusion, kind,
line2_text: The proper organs, proper powers assigned;

line1_text: Each seeming want compensated of course,
line2_text: Here with degrees of swiftness, there of force;

line1_text: All in exact proportion to the state;
line2_text: Nothing to add, and nothing to abate.

line1_text: Each beast, each insect, happy in its own:
line2_text: Is Heaven unkind to man, and man alone?

line1_text: Shall he alone, whom rational we call,
line2_text: Be pleased with nothing, if not blessed with all?

line1_text: The bliss of man (could pride that blessing find)
line2_text: Is not to act or think beyond mankind;

line1_text: No powers of body or of soul to share,
line2_text: But what his nature and his state can bear.

line1_text: Why has not man a microscopic eye?
line2_text: For this plain reason, man is not a fly.

line1_text: Say what the use, were finer optics given,
line2_text: To inspect a mite, not comprehend the heaven?

line1_text: Or touch, if tremblingly alive all o'er,
line2_text: To smart and agonize at every pore?

line1_text: Or quick effluvia darting through the brain,
line2_text: Die of a rose in aromatic pain?

line1_text: If Nature thundered in his opening ears,
line2_text: And stunned him with the music of the spheres,

line1_text: How would he wish that Heaven had left him still
line2_text: The whispering zephyr, and the purling rill?

line1_text: Who finds not Providence all good and wise,
line2_text: Alike in what it gives, and what denies?

line1_text: VII.  Far as Creation's ample range extends,
line2_text: The scale of sensual, mental powers ascends:

line1_text: Mark how it mounts, to man's imperial race,
line2_text: From the green myriads in the peopled grass:

line1_text: What modes of sight betwixt each wide extreme,
line2_text: The mole's dim curtain, and the lynx's beam:

line1_text: Of smell, the headlong lioness between,
line2_text: And hound sagacious on the tainted green:

line1_text: Of hearing, from the life that fills the flood,
line2_text: To that which warbles through the vernal wood:

line1_text: The spider's touch, how exquisitely fine!
line2_text: Feels at each thread, and lives along the line:

line1_text: In the nice bee, what sense so subtly true
line2_text: From poisonous herbs extracts the healing dew?

line1_text: How instinct varies in the grovelling swine,
line2_text: Compared, half-reasoning elephant, with thine!

line1_text: 'Twixt that, and reason, what a nice barrier,
line2_text: For ever separate, yet for ever near!

line1_text: Remembrance and reflection how allayed;
line2_text: What thin partitions sense from thought divide:

line1_text: And middle natures, how they long to join,
line2_text: Yet never passed the insuperable line!

line1_text: Without this just gradation, could they be
line2_text: Subjected, these to those, or all to thee?

line1_text: The powers of all subdued by thee alone,
line2_text: Is not thy reason all these powers in one?

line1_text: VIII.  See, through this air, this ocean, and this earth,
line2_text: All matter quick, and bursting into birth.

line1_text: Above, how high, progressive life may go!
line2_text: Around, how wide! how deep extend below?

line1_text: Vast chain of being! which from God began,
line2_text: Natures ethereal, human, angel, man,

line1_text: Beast, bird, fish, insect, what no eye can see,
line2_text: No glass can reach; from Infinite to thee,

line1_text: From thee to nothing.  On superior powers
line2_text: Were we to press, inferior might on ours:

line1_text: Or in the full creation leave a void,
line2_text: Where, one step broken, the great scale's destroyed:

line1_text: From Nature's chain whatever link you strike,
line2_text: Tenth or ten thousandth, breaks the chain alike.

line1_text: And, if each system in gradation roll
line2_text: Alike essential to the amazing whole,

line1_text: The least confusion but in one, not all
line2_text: That system only, but the whole must fall.

line1_text: Let earth unbalanced from her orbit fly,
line2_text: Planets and suns run lawless through the sky;

line1_text: Let ruling angels from their spheres be hurled,
line2_text: Being on being wrecked, and world on world;

line1_text: Heaven's whole foundations to their centre nod,
line2_text: And nature tremble to the throne of God.

line1_text: All this dread order break--for whom? for thee?
line2_text: Vile worm!--Oh, madness! pride! impiety!

line1_text: IX.  What if the foot, ordained the dust to tread,
line2_text: Or hand, to toil, aspired to be the head?

line1_text: What if the head, the eye, or ear repined
line2_text: To serve mere engines to the ruling mind?

line1_text: Just as absurd for any part to claim
line2_text: To be another, in this general frame:

line1_text: Just as absurd, to mourn the tasks or pains,
line2_text: The great directing Mind of All ordains.

line1_text: All are but parts of one stupendous whole,
line2_text: Whose body Nature is, and God the soul;

line1_text: That, changed through all, and yet in all the same;
line2_text: Great in the earth, as in the ethereal frame;

line1_text: Warms in the sun, refreshes in the breeze,
line2_text: Glows in the stars, and blossoms in the trees,

line1_text: Lives through all life, extends through all extent,
line2_text: Spreads undivided, operates unspent;

line1_text: Breathes in our soul, informs our mortal part,
line2_text: As full, as perfect, in a hair as heart:

line1_text: As full, as perfect, in vile man that mourns,
line2_text: As the rapt seraph that adores and burns:

line1_text: To him no high, no low, no great, no small;
line2_text: He fills, he bounds, connects, and equals all.

line1_text: X.  Cease, then, nor order imperfection name:
line2_text: Our proper bliss depends on what we blame.

line1_text: Know thy own point: this kind, this due degree
line2_text: Of blindness, weakness, Heaven bestows on thee.

line1_text: Submit.  In this, or any other sphere,
line2_text: Secure to be as blest as thou canst bear:

line1_text: Safe in the hand of one disposing Power,
line2_text: Or in the natal, or the mortal hour.

line1_text: All nature is but art, unknown to thee;
line2_text: All chance, direction, which thou canst not see;

line1_text: All discord, harmony not understood;
line2_text: All partial evil, universal good:

line1_text: And, spite of pride in erring reason's spite,
line2_text: One truth is clear, whatever is, is right.

line1_text: I.  Know, then, thyself, presume not God to scan;
line2_text: The proper study of mankind is man.

line1_text: Placed on this isthmus of a middle state,
line2_text: A being darkly wise, and rudely great:

line1_text: With too much knowledge for the sceptic side,
line2_text: With too much weakness for the stoic's pride,

line1_text: He hangs between; in doubt to act, or rest;
line2_text: In doubt to deem himself a god, or beast;

line1_text: In doubt his mind or body to prefer;
line2_text: Born but to die, and reasoning but to err;

line1_text: Alike in ignorance, his reason such,
line2_text: Whether he thinks too little, or too much:

line1_text: Chaos of thought and passion, all confused;
line2_text: Still by himself abused, or disabused;

line1_text: Created half to rise, and half to fall;
line2_text: Great lord of all things, yet a prey to all;

line1_text: Sole judge of truth, in endless error hurled:
line2_text: The glory, jest, and riddle of the world!

line1_text: Go, wondrous creature! mount where science guides,
line2_text: Go, measure earth, weigh air, and state the tides;

line1_text: Instruct the planets in what orbs to run,
line2_text: Correct old time, and regulate the sun;

line1_text: Go, soar with Plato to th' empyreal sphere,
line2_text: To the first good, first perfect, and first fair;

line1_text: Or tread the mazy round his followers trod,
line2_text: And quitting sense call imitating God;

line1_text: As Eastern priests in giddy circles run,
line2_text: And turn their heads to imitate the sun.

line1_text: Go, teach Eternal Wisdom how to rule--
line2_text: Then drop into thyself, and be a fool!

line1_text: Superior beings, when of late they saw
line2_text: A mortal man unfold all Nature's law,

line1_text: Admired such wisdom in an earthly shape
line2_text: And showed a Newton as we show an ape.

line1_text: Could he, whose rules the rapid comet bind,
line2_text: Describe or fix one movement of his mind?

line1_text: Who saw its fires here rise, and there descend,
line2_text: Explain his own beginning, or his end?

line1_text: Alas, what wonder! man's superior part
line2_text: Unchecked may rise, and climb from art to art;

line1_text: But when his own great work is but begun,
line2_text: What reason weaves, by passion is undone.

line1_text: Trace Science, then, with Modesty thy guide;
line2_text: First strip off all her equipage of pride;

line1_text: Deduct what is but vanity or dress,
line2_text: Or learning's luxury, or idleness;

line1_text: Or tricks to show the stretch of human brain,
line2_text: Mere curious pleasure, or ingenious pain;

line1_text: Expunge the whole, or lop th' excrescent parts
line2_text: Of all our vices have created arts;

line1_text: Then see how little the remaining sum,
line2_text: Which served the past, and must the times to come!

line1_text: II.  Two principles in human nature reign;
line2_text: Self-love to urge, and reason, to restrain;

line1_text: Nor this a good, nor that a bad we call,
line2_text: Each works its end, to move or govern all

line1_text: And to their proper operation still,
line2_text: Ascribe all good; to their improper, ill.

line1_text: Self-love, the spring of motion, acts the soul;
line2_text: Reason's comparing balance rules the whole.

line1_text: Man, but for that, no action could attend,
line2_text: And but for this, were active to no end:

line1_text: Fixed like a plant on his peculiar spot,
line2_text: To draw nutrition, propagate, and rot;

line1_text: Or, meteor-like, flame lawless through the void,
line2_text: Destroying others, by himself destroyed.

line1_text: Most strength the moving principle requires;
line2_text: Active its task, it prompts, impels, inspires.

line1_text: Sedate and quiet the comparing lies,
line2_text: Formed but to check, deliberate, and advise.

line1_text: Self-love still stronger, as its objects nigh;
line2_text: Reason's at distance, and in prospect lie:

line1_text: That sees immediate good by present sense;
line2_text: Reason, the future and the consequence.

line1_text: Thicker than arguments, temptations throng.
line2_text: At best more watchful this, but that more strong.

line1_text: The action of the stronger to suspend,
line2_text: Reason still use, to reason still attend.

line1_text: Attention, habit and experience gains;
line2_text: Each strengthens reason, and self-love restrains.

line1_text: Let subtle schoolmen teach these friends to fight,
line2_text: More studious to divide than to unite;

line1_text: And grace and virtue, sense and reason split,
line2_text: With all the rash dexterity of wit.

line1_text: Wits, just like fools, at war about a name,
line2_text: Have full as oft no meaning, or the same.

line1_text: Self-love and reason to one end aspire,
line2_text: Pain their aversion, pleasure their desire;

line1_text: But greedy that, its object would devour,
line2_text: This taste the honey, and not wound the flower:

line1_text: Pleasure, or wrong or rightly understood,
line2_text: Our greatest evil, or our greatest good.

line1_text: III.  Modes of self-love the passions we may call;
line2_text: 'Tis real good, or seeming, moves them all:

line1_text: But since not every good we can divide,
line2_text: And reason bids us for our own provide;

line1_text: Passions, though selfish, if their means be fair,
line2_text: List under Reason, and deserve her care;

line1_text: Those, that imparted, court a nobler aim,
line2_text: Exalt their kind, and take some virtue's name.

line1_text: In lazy apathy let stoics boast
line2_text: Their virtue fixed; 'tis fixed as in a frost;

line1_text: Contracted all, retiring to the breast;
line2_text: But strength of mind is exercise, not rest:

line1_text: The rising tempest puts in act the soul,
line2_text: Parts it may ravage, but preserves the whole.

line1_text: On life's vast ocean diversely we sail,
line2_text: Reason the card, but passion is the gale;

line1_text: Nor God alone in the still calm we find,
line2_text: He mounts the storm, and walks upon the wind.

line1_text: Passions, like elements, though born to fight,
line2_text: Yet, mixed and softened, in his work unite:

line1_text: These, 'tis enough to temper and employ;
line2_text: But what composes man, can man destroy?

line1_text: Suffice that Reason keep to Nature's road,
line2_text: Subject, compound them, follow her and God.

line1_text: Love, hope, and joy, fair pleasure's smiling train,
line2_text: Hate, fear, and grief, the family of pain,

line1_text: These mixed with art, and to due bounds confined,
line2_text: Make and maintain the balance of the mind;

line1_text: The lights and shades, whose well-accorded strife
line2_text: Gives all the strength and colour of our life.

line1_text: Pleasures are ever in our hands or eyes;
line2_text: And when in act they cease, in prospect rise:

line1_text: Present to grasp, and future still to find,
line2_text: The whole employ of body and of mind.

line1_text: All spread their charms, but charm not all alike;
line2_text: On different senses different objects strike;

line1_text: Hence different passions more or less inflame,
line2_text: As strong or weak, the organs of the frame;

line1_text: And hence once master passion in the breast,
line2_text: Like Aaron's serpent, swallows up the rest.

line1_text: As man, perhaps, the moment of his breath
line2_text: Receives the lurking principle of death;

line1_text: The young disease that must subdue at length,
line2_text: Grows with his growth, and strengthens with his strength:

line1_text: So, cast and mingled with his very frame,
line2_text: The mind's disease, its ruling passion came;

line1_text: Each vital humour which should feed the whole,
line2_text: Soon flows to this, in body and in soul:

line1_text: Whatever warms the heart, or fills the head,
line2_text: As the mind opens, and its functions spread,

line1_text: Imagination plies her dangerous art,
line2_text: And pours it all upon the peccant part.

line1_text: Nature its mother, habit is its nurse;
line2_text: Wit, spirit, faculties, but make it worse;

line1_text: Reason itself but gives it edge and power;
line2_text: As Heaven's blest beam turns vinegar more sour.

line1_text: We, wretched subjects, though to lawful sway,
line2_text: In this weak queen some favourite still obey:

line1_text: Ah! if she lend not arms, as well as rules,
line2_text: What can she more than tell us we are fools?

line1_text: Teach us to mourn our nature, not to mend,
line2_text: A sharp accuser, but a helpless friend!

line1_text: Or from a judge turn pleader, to persuade
line2_text: The choice we make, or justify it made;

line1_text: Proud of an easy conquest all along,
line2_text: She but removes weak passions for the strong;

line1_text: So, when small humours gather to a gout,
line2_text: The doctor fancies he has driven them out.

line1_text: Yes, Nature's road must ever be preferred;
line2_text: Reason is here no guide, but still a guard:

line1_text: 'Tis hers to rectify, not overthrow,
line2_text: And treat this passion more as friend than foe:

line1_text: A mightier power the strong direction sends,
line2_text: And several men impels to several ends:

line1_text: Like varying winds, by other passions tossed,
line2_text: This drives them constant to a certain coast.

line1_text: Let power or knowledge, gold or glory, please,
line2_text: Or (oft more strong than all) the love of ease;

line1_text: Through life 'tis followed, even at life's expense;
line2_text: The merchant's toil, the sage's indolence,

line1_text: The monk's humility, the hero's pride,
line2_text: All, all alike, find reason on their side.

line1_text: The eternal art, educing good from ill,
line2_text: Grafts on this passion our best principle:

line1_text: 'Tis thus the mercury of man is fixed,
line2_text: Strong grows the virtue with his nature mixed;

line1_text: The dross cements what else were too refined,
line2_text: And in one interest body acts with mind.

line1_text: As fruits, ungrateful to the planter's care,
line2_text: On savage stocks inserted, learn to bear;

line1_text: The surest virtues thus from passions shoot,
line2_text: Wild nature's vigour working at the root.

line1_text: What crops of wit and honesty appear
line2_text: From spleen, from obstinacy, hate, or fear!

line1_text: See anger, zeal and fortitude supply;
line2_text: Even avarice, prudence; sloth, philosophy;

line1_text: Lust, through some certain strainers well refined,
line2_text: Is gentle love, and charms all womankind;

line1_text: Envy, to which th' ignoble mind's a slave,
line2_text: Is emulation in the learned or brave;

line1_text: Nor virtue, male or female, can we name,
line2_text: But what will grow on pride, or grow on shame.

line1_text: Thus Nature gives us (let it check our pride)
line2_text: The virtue nearest to our vice allied:

line1_text: Reason the bias turns to good from ill
line2_text: And Nero reigns a Titus, if he will.

line1_text: The fiery soul abhorred in Catiline,
line2_text: In Decius charms, in Curtius is divine:

line1_text: The same ambition can destroy or save,
line2_text: And makes a patriot as it makes a knave.

line1_text: This light and darkness in our chaos joined,
line2_text: What shall divide?  The God within the mind.

line1_text: Extremes in nature equal ends produce,
line2_text: In man they join to some mysterious use;

line1_text: Though each by turns the other's bound invade,
line2_text: As, in some well-wrought picture, light and shade,

line1_text: And oft so mix, the difference is too nice
line2_text: Where ends the virtue or begins the vice.

line1_text: Fools! who from hence into the notion fall,
line2_text: That vice or virtue there is none at all.

line1_text: If white and black blend, soften, and unite
line2_text: A thousand ways, is there no black or white?

line1_text: Ask your own heart, and nothing is so plain;
line2_text: 'Tis to mistake them, costs the time and pain.

line1_text: Vice is a monster of so frightful mien,
line2_text: As, to be hated, needs but to be seen;

line1_text: Yet seen too oft, familiar with her face,
line2_text: We first endure, then pity, then embrace.

line1_text: But where th' extreme of vice, was ne'er agreed:
line2_text: Ask where's the north? at York, 'tis on the Tweed;

line1_text: In Scotland, at the Orcades; and there,
line2_text: At Greenland, Zembla, or the Lord knows where.

line1_text: No creature owns it in the first degree,
line2_text: But thinks his neighbour farther gone than he;

line1_text: Even those who dwell beneath its very zone,
line2_text: Or never feel the rage, or never own;

line1_text: What happier nations shrink at with affright,
line2_text: The hard inhabitant contends is right.

line1_text: Virtuous and vicious every man must be,
line2_text: Few in th' extreme, but all in the degree,

line1_text: The rogue and fool by fits is fair and wise;
line2_text: And even the best, by fits, what they despise.

line1_text: 'Tis but by parts we follow good or ill;
line2_text: For, vice or virtue, self directs it still;

line1_text: Each individual seeks a several goal;
line2_text: But Heaven's great view is one, and that the whole.

line1_text: That counter-works each folly and caprice;
line2_text: That disappoints th' effect of every vice;

line1_text: That, happy frailties to all ranks applied,
line2_text: Shame to the virgin, to the matron pride,

line1_text: Fear to the statesman, rashness to the chief,
line2_text: To kings presumption, and to crowds belief:

line1_text: That, virtue's ends from vanity can raise,
line2_text: Which seeks no interest, no reward but praise;

line1_text: And build on wants, and on defects of mind,
line2_text: The joy, the peace, the glory of mankind.

line1_text: Heaven forming each on other to depend,
line2_text: A master, or a servant, or a friend,

line1_text: Bids each on other for assistance call,
line2_text: Till one man's weakness grows the strength of all.

line1_text: Wants, frailties, passions, closer still ally
line2_text: The common interest, or endear the tie.

line1_text: To these we owe true friendship, love sincere,
line2_text: Each home-felt joy that life inherits here;

line1_text: Yet from the same we learn, in its decline,
line2_text: Those joys, those loves, those interests to resign;

line1_text: Taught half by reason, half by mere decay,
line2_text: To welcome death, and calmly pass away.

line1_text: Whate'er the passion, knowledge, fame, or pelf,
line2_text: Not one will change his neighbour with himself.

line1_text: The learned is happy nature to explore,
line2_text: The fool is happy that he knows no more;

line1_text: The rich is happy in the plenty given,
line2_text: The poor contents him with the care of Heaven.

line1_text: See the blind beggar dance, the cripple sing,
line2_text: The sot a hero, lunatic a king;

line1_text: The starving chemist in his golden views
line2_text: Supremely blest, the poet in his muse.

line1_text: See some strange comfort every state attend,
line2_text: And pride bestowed on all, a common friend;

line1_text: See some fit passion every age supply,
line2_text: Hope travels through, nor quits us when we die.

line1_text: Behold the child, by Nature's kindly law,
line2_text: Pleased with a rattle, tickled with a straw:

line1_text: Some livelier plaything gives his youth delight,
line2_text: A little louder, but as empty quite:

line1_text: Scarves, garters, gold, amuse his riper stage,
line2_text: And beads and prayer-books are the toys of age:

line1_text: Pleased with this bauble still, as that before;
line2_text: Till tired he sleeps, and life's poor play is o'er.

line1_text: Meanwhile opinion gilds with varying rays
line2_text: Those painted clouds that beautify our days;

line1_text: Each want of happiness by hope supplied,
line2_text: And each vacuity of sense by pride:

line1_text: These build as fast as knowledge can destroy;
line2_text: In folly's cup still laughs the bubble, joy;

line1_text: One prospect lost, another still we gain;
line2_text: And not a vanity is given in vain;

line1_text: Even mean self-love becomes, by force divine,
line2_text: The scale to measure others' wants by thine.

line1_text: See! and confess, one comfort still must rise,
line2_text: 'Tis this, though man's a fool, yet God is wise.

line1_text: Here, then, we rest: "The Universal Cause
line2_text: Acts to one end, but acts by various laws."

line1_text: In all the madness of superfluous health,
line2_text: The trim of pride, the impudence of wealth,

line1_text: Let this great truth be present night and day;
line2_text: But most be present, if we preach or pray.

line1_text: Look round our world; behold the chain of love
line2_text: Combining all below and all above.

line1_text: See plastic Nature working to this end,
line2_text: The single atoms each to other tend,

line1_text: Attract, attracted to, the next in place
line2_text: Formed and impelled its neighbour to embrace.

line1_text: See matter next, with various life endued,
line2_text: Press to one centre still, the general good.

line1_text: See dying vegetables life sustain,
line2_text: See life dissolving vegetate again:

line1_text: All forms that perish other forms supply
line2_text: (By turns we catch the vital breath, and die),

line1_text: Like bubbles on the sea of matter borne,
line2_text: They rise, they break, and to that sea return.

line1_text: Nothing is foreign: parts relate to whole;
line2_text: One all-extending, all-preserving soul

line1_text: Connects each being, greatest with the least;
line2_text: Made beast in aid of man, and man of beast;

line1_text: All served, all serving: nothing stands alone;
line2_text: The chain holds on, and where it ends, unknown.

line1_text: Has God, thou fool! worked solely for thy Thy good,
line2_text: Thy joy, thy pastime, thy attire, thy food?

line1_text: Who for thy table feeds the wanton fawn,
line2_text: For him as kindly spread the flowery lawn:

line1_text: Is it for thee the lark ascends and sings?
line2_text: Joy tunes his voice, joy elevates his wings.

line1_text: Is it for thee the linnet pours his throat?
line2_text: Loves of his own and raptures swell the note.

line1_text: The bounding steed you pompously bestride,
line2_text: Shares with his lord the pleasure and the pride.

line1_text: Is thine alone the seed that strews the plain?
line2_text: The birds of heaven shall vindicate their grain.

line1_text: Thine the full harvest of the golden year?
line2_text: Part pays, and justly, the deserving steer:

line1_text: The hog, that ploughs not nor obeys thy call,
line2_text: Lives on the labours of this lord of all.

line1_text: Know, Nature's children all divide her care;
line2_text: The fur that warms a monarch, warmed a bear.

line1_text: While man exclaims, "See all things for my use!"
line2_text: "See man for mine!" replies a pampered goose:

line1_text: And just as short of reason he must fall,
line2_text: Who thinks all made for one, not one for all.

line1_text: Grant that the powerful still the weak control;
line2_text: Be man the wit and tyrant of the whole:

line1_text: Nature that tyrant checks; he only knows,
line2_text: And helps, another creature's wants and woes.

line1_text: Say, will the falcon, stooping from above,
line2_text: Smit with her varying plumage, spare the dove?

line1_text: Admires the jay the insect's gilded wings?
line2_text: Or hears the hawk when Philomela sings?

line1_text: Man cares for all: to birds he gives his woods,
line2_text: To beasts his pastures, and to fish his floods;

line1_text: For some his interest prompts him to provide,
line2_text: For more his pleasure, yet for more his pride:

line1_text: All feed on one vain patron, and enjoy
line2_text: The extensive blessing of his luxury.

line1_text: That very life his learned hunger craves,
line2_text: He saves from famine, from the savage saves;

line1_text: Nay, feasts the animal he dooms his feast,
line2_text: And, till he ends the being, makes it blest;

line1_text: Which sees no more the stroke, or feels the pain,
line2_text: Than favoured man by touch ethereal slain.

line1_text: The creature had his feast of life before;
line2_text: Thou too must perish when thy feast is o'er!

line1_text: To each unthinking being, Heaven, a friend,
line2_text: Gives not the useless knowledge of its end:

line1_text: To man imparts it; but with such a view
line2_text: As, while he dreads it, makes him hope it too;

line1_text: The hour concealed, and so remote the fear,
line2_text: Death still draws nearer, never seeming near.

line1_text: Great standing miracle! that Heaven assigned
line2_text: Its only thinking thing this turn of mind.

line1_text: II.  Whether with reason, or with instinct blest,
line2_text: Know, all enjoy that power which suits them best;

line1_text: To bliss alike by that direction tend,
line2_text: And find the means proportioned to their end.

line1_text: Say, where full instinct is the unerring guide,
line2_text: What pope or council can they need beside?

line1_text: Reason, however able, cool at best,
line2_text: Cares not for service, or but serves when pressed,

line1_text: Stays till we call, and then not often near;
line2_text: But honest instinct comes a volunteer,

line1_text: Sure never to o'er-shoot, but just to hit;
line2_text: While still too wide or short is human wit;

line1_text: Sure by quick nature happiness to gain,
line2_text: Which heavier reason labours at in vain,

line1_text: This too serves always, reason never long;
line2_text: One must go right, the other may go wrong.

line1_text: See then the acting and comparing powers
line2_text: One in their nature, which are two in ours;

line1_text: And reason raise o'er instinct as you can,
line2_text: In this 'tis God directs, in that 'tis man.

line1_text: Who taught the nations of the field and wood
line2_text: To shun their poison, and to choose their food?

line1_text: Prescient, the tides or tempests to withstand,
line2_text: Build on the wave, or arch beneath the sand?

line1_text: Who made the spider parallels design,
line2_text: Sure as Demoivre, without rule or line?

line1_text: Who did the stork, Columbus-like, explore
line2_text: Heavens not his own, and worlds unknown before?

line1_text: Who calls the council, states the certain day,
line2_text: Who forms the phalanx, and who points the way?

line1_text: III.  God in the nature of each being founds
line2_text: Its proper bliss, and sets its proper bounds:

line1_text: But as He framed a whole, the whole to bless,
line2_text: On mutual wants built mutual happiness:

line1_text: So from the first, eternal order ran,
line2_text: And creature linked to creature, man to man.

line1_text: Whate'er of life all-quickening ether keeps,
line2_text: Or breathes through air, or shoots beneath the deeps,

line1_text: Or pours profuse on earth, one nature feeds
line2_text: The vital flame, and swells the genial seeds.

line1_text: Not man alone, but all that roam the wood,
line2_text: Or wing the sky, or roll along the flood,

line1_text: Each loves itself, but not itself alone,
line2_text: Each sex desires alike, till two are one.

line1_text: Nor ends the pleasure with the fierce embrace;
line2_text: They love themselves, a third time, in their race.

line1_text: Thus beast and bird their common charge attend,
line2_text: The mothers nurse it, and the sires defend;

line1_text: The young dismissed to wander earth or air,
line2_text: There stops the instinct, and there ends the care;

line1_text: The link dissolves, each seeks a fresh embrace,
line2_text: Another love succeeds, another race.

line1_text: A longer care man's helpless kind demands;
line2_text: That longer care contracts more lasting bands:

line1_text: Reflection, reason, still the ties improve,
line2_text: At once extend the interest and the love;

line1_text: With choice we fix, with sympathy we burn;
line2_text: Each virtue in each passion takes its turn;

line1_text: And still new needs, new helps, new habits rise.
line2_text: That graft benevolence on charities.

line1_text: Still as one brood, and as another rose,
line2_text: These natural love maintained, habitual those.

line1_text: The last, scarce ripened into perfect man,
line2_text: Saw helpless him from whom their life began:

line1_text: Memory and forecast just returns engage,
line2_text: That pointed back to youth, this on to age;

line1_text: While pleasure, gratitude, and hope combined,
line2_text: Still spread the interest, and preserved the kind.

line1_text: IV.  Nor think, in Nature's state they blindly trod;
line2_text: The state of nature was the reign of God:

line1_text: Self-love and social at her birth began,
line2_text: Union the bond of all things, and of man.

line1_text: Pride then was not; nor arts, that pride to aid;
line2_text: Man walked with beast, joint tenant of the shade;

line1_text: The same his table, and the same his bed;
line2_text: No murder clothed him, and no murder fed.

line1_text: In the same temple, the resounding wood,
line2_text: All vocal beings hymned their equal God:

line1_text: The shrine with gore unstained, with gold undressed,
line2_text: Unbribed, unbloody, stood the blameless priest:

line1_text: Heaven's attribute was universal care,
line2_text: And man's prerogative to rule, but spare.

line1_text: Ah! how unlike the man of times to come!
line2_text: Of half that live the butcher and the tomb;

line1_text: Who, foe to nature, hears the general groan,
line2_text: Murders their species, and betrays his own.

line1_text: But just disease to luxury succeeds,
line2_text: And every death its own avenger breeds;

line1_text: The fury-passions from that blood began,
line2_text: And turned on man a fiercer savage, man.

line1_text: See him from Nature rising slow to art!
line2_text: To copy instinct then was reason's part;

line1_text: Thus then to man the voice of Nature spake--
line2_text: "Go, from the creatures thy instructions take:

line1_text: Learn from the birds what food the thickets yield;
line2_text: Learn from the beasts the physic of the field;

line1_text: Thy arts of building from the bee receive;
line2_text: Learn of the mole to plough, the worm to weave;

line1_text: Learn of the little nautilus to sail,
line2_text: Spread the thin oar, and catch the driving gale.

line1_text: Here too all forms of social union find,
line2_text: And hence let reason, late, instruct mankind:

line1_text: Here subterranean works and cities see;
line2_text: There towns aerial on the waving tree.

line1_text: Learn each small people's genius, policies,
line2_text: The ant's republic, and the realm of bees;

line1_text: How those in common all their wealth bestow,
line2_text: And anarchy without confusion know;

line1_text: And these for ever, though a monarch reign,
line2_text: Their separate cells and properties maintain.

line1_text: Mark what unvaried laws preserve each state,
line2_text: Laws wise as nature, and as fixed as fate.

line1_text: In vain thy reason finer webs shall draw,
line2_text: Entangle justice in her net of law,

line1_text: And right, too rigid, harden into wrong;
line2_text: Still for the strong too weak, the weak too strong.

line1_text: Yet go! and thus o'er all the creatures sway,
line2_text: Thus let the wiser make the rest obey;

line1_text: And, for those arts mere instinct could afford,
line2_text: Be crowned as monarchs, or as gods adored."

line1_text: V.  Great Nature spoke; observant men obeyed;
line2_text: Cities were built, societies were made:

line1_text: Here rose one little state: another near
line2_text: Grew by like means, and joined, through love or fear.

line1_text: Did here the trees with ruddier burdens bend,
line2_text: And there the streams in purer rills descend?

line1_text: What war could ravish, commerce could bestow,
line2_text: And he returned a friend, who came a foe.

line1_text: Converse and love mankind might strongly draw,
line2_text: When love was liberty, and Nature law.

line1_text: Thus States were formed; the name of king unknown,
line2_text: 'Till common interest placed the sway in one.

line1_text: 'Twas virtue only (or in arts or arms,
line2_text: Diffusing blessings, or averting harms)

line1_text: The same which in a sire the sons obeyed,
line2_text: A prince the father of a people made.

line1_text: VI.  Till then, by Nature crowned, each patriarch sate,
line2_text: King, priest, and parent of his growing state;

line1_text: On him, their second providence, they hung,
line2_text: Their law his eye, their oracle his tongue.

line1_text: He from the wondering furrow called the food,
line2_text: Taught to command the fire, control the flood,

line1_text: Draw forth the monsters of the abyss profound,
line2_text: Or fetch the aerial eagle to the ground.

line1_text: Till drooping, sickening, dying they began
line2_text: Whom they revered as God to mourn as man:

line1_text: Then, looking up, from sire to sire, explored
line2_text: One great first Father, and that first adored.

line1_text: Or plain tradition that this all begun,
line2_text: Conveyed unbroken faith from sire to son;

line1_text: The worker from the work distinct was known,
line2_text: And simple reason never sought but one:

line1_text: Ere wit oblique had broke that steady light,
line2_text: Man, like his Maker, saw that all was right;

line1_text: To virtue, in the paths of pleasure, trod,
line2_text: And owned a Father when he owned a God.

line1_text: Love all the faith, and all the allegiance then;
line2_text: For Nature knew no right divine in men,

line1_text: No ill could fear in God; and understood
line2_text: A sovereign being but a sovereign good.

line1_text: True faith, true policy, united ran,
line2_text: This was but love of God, and this of man.

line1_text: Who first taught souls enslaved, and realms undone,
line2_text: The enormous faith of many made for one;

line1_text: That proud exception to all Nature's laws,
line2_text: To invert the world, and counter-work its cause?

line1_text: Force first made conquest, and that conquest, law;
line2_text: Till superstition taught the tyrant awe,

line1_text: Then shared the tyranny, then lent it aid,
line2_text: And gods of conquerors, slaves of subjects made:

line1_text: She, 'midst the lightning's blaze, and thunder's sound,
line2_text: When rocked the mountains, and when groaned the ground,

line1_text: She taught the weak to bend, the proud to pray,
line2_text: To power unseen, and mightier far than they:

line1_text: She, from the rending earth and bursting skies,
line2_text: Saw gods descend, and fiends infernal rise:

line1_text: Here fixed the dreadful, there the blest abodes;
line2_text: Fear made her devils, and weak hope her gods;

line1_text: Gods partial, changeful, passionate, unjust,
line2_text: Whose attributes were rage, revenge, or lust;

line1_text: Such as the souls of cowards might conceive,
line2_text: And, formed like tyrants, tyrants would believe.

line1_text: Zeal then, not charity, became the guide;
line2_text: And hell was built on spite, and heaven on pride,

line1_text: Then sacred seemed the ethereal vault no more;
line2_text: Altars grew marble then, and reeked with gore;

line1_text: Then first the flamen tasted living food;
line2_text: Next his grim idol smeared with human blood;

line1_text: With heaven's own thunders shook the world below,
line2_text: And played the god an engine on his foe.

line1_text: So drives self-love, through just and through unjust,
line2_text: To one man's power, ambition, lucre, lust:

line1_text: The same self-love, in all, becomes the cause
line2_text: Of what restrains him, government and laws.

line1_text: For, what one likes if others like as well,
line2_text: What serves one will when many wills rebel?

line1_text: How shall he keep, what, sleeping or awake,
line2_text: A weaker may surprise, a stronger take?

line1_text: His safety must his liberty restrain:
line2_text: All join to guard what each desires to gain.

line1_text: Forced into virtue thus by self-defence,
line2_text: Even kings learned justice and benevolence:

line1_text: Self-love forsook the path it first pursued,
line2_text: And found the private in the public good.

line1_text: 'Twas then, the studious head or generous mind,
line2_text: Follower of God, or friend of human-kind,

line1_text: Poet or patriot, rose but to restore
line2_text: The faith and moral Nature gave before;

line1_text: Re-lumed her ancient light, not kindled new;
line2_text: If not God's image, yet His shadow drew:

line1_text: Taught power's due use to people and to kings,
line2_text: Taught nor to slack, nor strain its tender strings,

line1_text: The less, or greater, set so justly true,
line2_text: That touching one must strike the other too;

line1_text: Till jarring interests, of themselves create
line2_text: The according music of a well-mixed state.

line1_text: Such is the world's great harmony, that springs
line2_text: From order, union, full consent of things:

line1_text: Where small and great, where weak and mighty, made
line2_text: To serve, not suffer, strengthen, not invade;

line1_text: More powerful each as needful to the rest,
line2_text: And, in proportion as it blesses, blest;

line1_text: Draw to one point, and to one centre bring
line2_text: Beast, man, or angel, servant, lord, or king.

line1_text: For forms of government let fools contest;
line2_text: Whate'er is best administered is best:

line1_text: For modes of faith let graceless zealots fight;
line2_text: His can't be wrong whose life is in the right:

line1_text: In faith and hope the world will disagree,
line2_text: But all mankind's concern is charity:

line1_text: All must be false that thwart this one great end;
line2_text: And all of God, that bless mankind or mend.

line1_text: Man, like the generous vine, supported lives;
line2_text: The strength he gains is from the embrace he gives.

line1_text: On their own axis as the planets run,
line2_text: Yet make at once their circle round the sun;

line1_text: So two consistent motions act the soul;
line2_text: And one regards itself, and one the whole.

line1_text: Thus God and Nature linked the general frame,
line2_text: And bade self-love and social be the same.

line1_text: Oh, happiness, our being's end and aim!
line2_text: Good, pleasure, ease, content! whate'er thy name:

line1_text: That something still which prompts the eternal sigh,
line2_text: For which we bear to live, or dare to die,

line1_text: Which still so near us, yet beyond us lies,
line2_text: O'erlooked, seen double, by the fool, and wise.

line1_text: Plant of celestial seed! if dropped below,
line2_text: Say, in what mortal soil thou deign'st to grow?

line1_text: Fair opening to some Court's propitious shine,
line2_text: Or deep with diamonds in the flaming mine?

line1_text: Twined with the wreaths Parnassian laurels yield,
line2_text: Or reaped in iron harvests of the field?

line1_text: Where grows?--where grows it not?  If vain our toil,
line2_text: We ought to blame the culture, not the soil:

line1_text: Fixed to no spot is happiness sincere,
line2_text: 'Tis nowhere to be found, or everywhere;

line1_text: 'Tis never to be bought, but always free,
line2_text: And fled from monarchs, St. John! dwells with thee.

line1_text: Ask of the learned the way?  The learned are blind;
line2_text: This bids to serve, and that to shun mankind;

line2_text: Some, swelled to gods, confess even virtue vain;

line1_text: Or indolent, to each extreme they fall,

line1_text: Who thus define it, say they more or less

line1_text: And mourn our various portions as we please,

line1_text: And makes what happiness we justly call

line1_text: There's not a blessing individuals find,

line1_text: No bandit fierce, no tyrant mad with pride,

line1_text: Order is Heaven's first law; and this confest,
line2_text: Some are, and must be, greater than the rest,

line1_text: More rich, more wise; but who infers from hence
line2_text: That such are happier, shocks all common sense.

line1_text: Heaven to mankind impartial we confess,
line2_text: If all are equal in their happiness:

line1_text: But mutual wants this happiness increase;
line2_text: All Nature's difference keeps all Nature's peace.

line1_text: Condition, circumstance is not the thing;
line2_text: Bliss is the same in subject or in king,

line1_text: In who obtain defence, or who defend,
line2_text: In him who is, or him who finds a friend:

line1_text: Heaven breathes through every member of the whole
line2_text: One common blessing, as one common soul.

line1_text: But fortune's gifts if each alike possessed,
line2_text: And each were equal, must not all contest?

line1_text: If then to all men happiness was meant,
line2_text: God in externals could not place content.

line1_text: Fortune her gifts may variously dispose,
line2_text: And these be happy called, unhappy those;

line1_text: But Heaven's just balance equal will appear,
line2_text: While those are placed in hope, and these in fear:

line1_text: Nor present good or ill, the joy or curse,
line2_text: But future views of better or of worse,

line1_text: Oh, sons of earth! attempt ye still to rise,
line2_text: By mountains piled on mountains, to the skies,

line1_text: Heaven still with laughter the vain toil surveys,
line2_text: And buries madmen in the heaps they raise.

line1_text: Know, all the good that individuals find,
line2_text: Or God and Nature meant to mere mankind,

line1_text: Reason's whole pleasure, all the joys of sense,
line2_text: Lie in three words, health, peace, and competence.

line1_text: But health consists with temperance alone;
line2_text: And peace, oh, virtue! peace is all thy own.

line1_text: The good or bad the gifts of fortune gain;
line2_text: But these less taste them, as they worse obtain.

line1_text: Say, in pursuit of profit or delight,
line2_text: Who risk the most, that take wrong means, or right;

line1_text: Of vice or virtue, whether blessed or cursed,
line2_text: Which meets contempt, or which compassion first?

line1_text: Count all the advantage prosperous vice attains,
line2_text: 'Tis but what virtue flies from and disdains:

line1_text: And grant the bad what happiness they would,
line2_text: One they must want, which is, to pass for good.

line1_text: Oh, blind to truth, and God's whole scheme below,
line2_text: Who fancy bliss to vice, to virtue woe!

line1_text: Who sees and follows that great scheme the best,
line2_text: Best knows the blessing, and will most be blest.

line1_text: But fools the good alone unhappy call,
line2_text: For ills or accidents that chance to all.

line1_text: See Falkland dies, the virtuous and the just!

line1_text: See Sidney bleeds amid the martial strife!
line2_text: Was this their virtue, or contempt of life?

line1_text: Say, was it virtue, more though Heaven ne'er gave,
line2_text: Lamented Digby! sunk thee to the grave?

line1_text: Tell me, if virtue made the son expire,
line2_text: Why, full of days and honour, lives the sire?

line1_text: Why drew Marseilles' good bishop purer breath,

line1_text: Or why so long (in life if long can be)
line2_text: Lent Heaven a parent to the poor and me?

line1_text: What makes all physical or moral ill?
line2_text: There deviates Nature, and here wanders will.

line1_text: God sends not ill; if rightly understood,
line2_text: Or partial ill is universal good,

line1_text: Or change admits, or Nature lets it fall;
line2_text: Short, and but rare, till man improved it all.

line1_text: We just as wisely might of Heaven complain

line1_text: On air or sea new motions be imprest,

line1_text: When the loose mountain trembles from on high,

line1_text: "What differ more (you cry) than crown and cowl?"
line2_text: I'll tell you, friend! a wise man and a fool.
